    1. [9]Home
    2. MIT***s position on why graduate students with MIT fellowships should
       not be included in the MIT GSU-UE***s proposed bargaining unit

  MIT***s position on why graduate students with MIT fellowships should not be
            included in the MIT GSU-UE***s proposed bargaining unit

   The following statement explains why MIT***s senior leadership does not
   think students supported by MIT fellowship awards (but who do not also
   have partial research assistant (RA), teaching assistant (TA), or
   Instructor G appointments) are eligible to be part of the bargaining unit
   represented by the MIT Graduate Student Union and United Electrical,
   Radio, and Machine Workers of America (MIT GSU-UE). MIT has asked the
   National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) to confirm that fellows are not
   employees under federal rules.

   The main points are:

     o All students have academic relationships with MIT; not all have
       employment relationships with MIT.
     o Applying a union labor process to a student body requires
       distinguishing between those who are student-employees and those who
       are students only. The National Labor Relations Act does not cover
       students but only student employees.**
     o Because of this, the MIT GSU-UE***s proposed unit would not include
       over 2,000 graduate students supported by full external fellowships
       and tuition-only fellowships, as well as those who are self-funded.**
     o Similarly, MIT senior leaders believe that students on MIT fellowship
       awards are not student-employees. They do not have service
       requirements, only the rigorous academic expectations required of all
       students.
     o The distinction between RAs/TAs and fellows also exists within federal
       research administration requirements, immigration regulations, and
       federal taxation rules, all of which MIT is required to follow.
     o MIT is asking the NLRB to confirm that graduate students on MIT
       fellowship awards are not employees under federal labor rules,
       consistent with other federal policies.
     o Being in the bargaining unit could strip fellows of some flexibilities
       and benefits that come with fellowship awards.**

All students have academic relationships with MIT; not all have employment
relationships with MIT

   Graduate student unionization involves a labor bargaining process that is
   fundamentally about negotiating the ***terms and conditions of
   employment.*** While many graduate students have an employment
   relationship with MIT, others do not. All students have an academic
   relationship with MIT. But only student-employees can organize and become
   part of a labor union. This means that both the MIT GSU-UE and MIT need to
   distinguish between those who are student-employees and those who are
   students only. **

The MIT GSU-UE***s desired bargaining unit would still exclude over 2,000
graduate students

   Because federal labor rules apply only to employees, the MIT GSU-UE***s
   desired bargaining unit (RAs, TAs, Instructor Gs, and fellows) would still
   not include over 2,000 MIT graduate students.

   The students who the MIT GSU-UE excludes are those who receive full
   fellowship support from external sources (e.g., certain awards from US
   federal agencies, foreign government agencies, corporations, or
   foundations); those on tuition-only fellowships; and those who are
   self-funded. These students conduct research and teaching as required by
   their academic programs, just like students who receive fellowship awards
   from MIT.**

   MIT senior leaders agree with the MIT GSU-UE that students on external
   fellowships, tuition-only fellowships, and self-funding are not employees
   under federal labor rules. Institute leadership further believes that MIT
   fellows also fall into the non-employee category.

Asking the NLRB to confirm that fellows are not employees under federal rules

   The NLRB has ruled that a graduate student is an employee and eligible to
   unionize if the university:

     o Pays the student;
     o Directs and controls the student***s work; and**
     o Requires specific services be performed as a condition of receiving
       their funding.

   MIT senior leaders do not believe that students on MIT fellowship awards
   are employees under this rule. They are asking the NLRB to confirm that.

   MIT is not alone in seeing a distinction between graduate fellows and
   student-employees. The graduate student union at the University of Iowa
   *** which is affiliated with the UE *** does not include fellows. The same
   is true at Brown University, the University of Massachusetts, and other
   schools.

   Similarly, at Harvard and Columbia, some graduate students are provided
   financial support to pursue their academic programs but are not included
   in the bargaining units at those schools.

   This distinction between RAs/TAs and fellows also exists in several other
   important contexts, including federal research administration
   requirements, immigration regulations, and federal taxation rules. **

Comparing fellowship awards with TA/RA appointments and external funding

   The below table illustrates the similarities and key differences between
   appointment and award types at MIT.

   Importantly, RAs and TAs are generally required to perform specific
   services, or work on specific research projects, in order to receive their
   assistantship funding. This is not true of fellows and self-funded
   students. The concept of ***pay for services rendered*** is at the core of
   what it means to be an employee under federal labor law.

                                TA  RA  MIT Fellowship External
                                                       Fellowship/Self-Funded
   Take required courses        Yes Yes Yes            Yes
   Conduct research for thesis  Yes Yes Yes            Yes
   Provide specific services,
   or work on certain research  Yes Yes No             No
   projects, in order to
   receive funding**
   Funding is generally
   portable and is awarded to
   the student independent of   N/A No  Yes            Yes
   the specific research
   project they pursue
   Can lose funding for
   unsatisfactory academic      Yes Yes Yes            Yes
   performance
   Can lose funding for
   unsatisfactory performance   Yes Yes No             No
   of service requirements
   Funding controlled by PI     N/A Yes No             No
   Verify employment
   eligibility through I-9      Yes Yes No             No
   forms
   Receive W-2s from MIT for    Yes Yes No             No
   employment income**
   Stipend and tuition are
   charged to federal research  N/A Yes No             No
   contracts and grants

What are some benefits that fellowship award holders have by being outside of
the bargaining unit?

   Fellowship awards are MIT***s most flexible form of financial assistance
   because they do not come with service requirements, only the rigorous
   academic expectations required of all students. Fellowships afford
   students the flexibility to choose among different specific research
   projects. For these reasons, fellowships are regarded as the most
   attractive form of funding by students across the world when they consider
   admission decisions at MIT and elsewhere, and why fellowships are often
   awarded early in a student***s academic progression.

   It is also why fellowships are frequently awarded in [10]MIT***s
   Guaranteed Transitional Support Program when students want to change
   research groups *** explicitly to remove any service requirements.

   MIT***s international students who are awarded fellowships also depend on
   the flexibility they provide, especially those with spouses or partners
   who cannot work. That is because federal immigration law limits on-campus
   employment opportunities for international students to 20 hours per week
   during the fall and spring semesters. International students on full RA
   and TA appointments are not permitted to take on other on-campus
   employment opportunities during these terms. If fellowships are deemed to
   require services and are included in the bargaining unit, then
   international students awarded full fellowships would be subject to the
   same employment restrictions as RAs and TAs.**

   In short, in a unionized setting, some of the flexibility fellows
   currently enjoy would likely be eliminated. This is why, in addition to
   their interpretation of federal rules, MIT senior leaders believe it is
   better for students with fellowship awards to remain outside the
   bargaining unit and why they have asked the NLRB to decide this matter.

   Community members with questions about unions and unionization that are
   not addressed on this website may contact**[11]gradunionquestions@mit.edu.

