Notice of subpoena requiring MIT to share graduate student information with NLRB
                                     and UE

   To MIT graduate students,**

   Below, please find important information about MIT***s obligation to
   provide personally-identifiable information about its graduate students to
   the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) and United Electrical, Radio and
   Machine Workers of America (UE). This requirement stems from [8]the
   graduate student unionization effort that is underway.

Subpoena requires MIT to provide graduate student information to the NLRB and UE
by noon on February 17th

   As part of the process initiated by the United Electrical, Radio and
   Machine Workers of America (UE), MIT recently received a subpoena from the
   NLRB which requires the Institute to provide students*** names, work
   locations/departments, and job classifications/appointment types to the
   NLRB and UE on or before noon on February 17th. A [9]copy of the
   subpoena**is available for review.

   Once the NLRB determines who is eligible to vote in the union election,
   the subpoena also requires MIT to disclose additional information about
   those eligible voters. This additional information, which includes home
   addresses, personal email addresses, and home and personal telephone
   numbers, will be disclosed at a later date. Please note that, once this
   information is provided, it may be used by the UE as part of their
   campaigning efforts.

Notice of disclosure under MIT policy and federal student privacy rules**

   The information sought by the NLRB subpoena constitutes ***education
   records*** as defined by the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act
   (***FERPA***) (20 U.S.C. ** 1232g(b)(2) and 34 C.F.R. Part 99), a federal
   law that protects the privacy of student records. Therefore, consistent
   with FERPA and [10]MIT***s policy on the privacy of student records, MIT
   is notifying you about the subpoena and the Institute***s obligation to
   produce the information described above.

   There is no action required on your part. However, if you wish to seek
   protective action to prevent some or all of these disclosures, you may
   have to initiate a separate court action. You should take this step as
   soon as possible. MIT will produce the initial set of information
   requested by the subpoena no earlier than the morning of February 17.
   Please note that MIT requested and received additional time (to February
   17) to produce the requested information, so that MIT could provide this
   notice and afford students time to seek protective action. MIT will
   produce the additional, more comprehensive set of information about
   eligible voters at a later date, which will be determined by the NLRB.

   If you have any questions or concerns, please reach out to
   [11]gradunionquestions@mit.edu. MIT encourages all graduate students to
   learn more about the unionization process by visiting
   [12]grad-union.mit.edu.
   **

